Source: United States Department of Agriculture-APHIS, Veterinary Services,
Emergency Management Warning 11, Fri 31 Aug 2001 [edited
<http://www.aphis.usda.gov/oa/wnv/wnvemw11.html>

West Nile Virus Confirmed Positive in Horse in Kentucky
-------------------------------------------------------
The State of Kentucky has announced that a horse residing in Bourbon
County, Kentucky, has been confirmed as positive for West Nile virus
infection. This is the first equine case of clinical West Nile virus
infection ever detected in Kentucky.
The horse is a 3-year-old mare that developed encephalitis but is
apparently now recovering. A definitive date of onset of illness is not yet
known, but it was on or before 23 Aug 2001. There is no history of recent
travel of the horse outside of Kentucky.
West Nile virus infection was confirmed in at the National Veterinary
Services Laboratories (NVSL). Both West Nile virus IgM-capture
enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA) and plaque-reduction
neutralization test were positive on a serum sample.
More information on West Nile virus including links to State and local West
Nile virus web pages is available on the APHIS website at:
<http://www.aphis.usda.gov/oa/wnv/index.html>.
